data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. In .NET 10 you could call `EnableSynchronousIO()` (or the equivalent option) to let sync methods like `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` work by internally wrapping the async Cosmos SDK calls. In .NET 11, that escape hatch is gone.

Every synchronous LINQ/save call against the Cosmos provider will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — there is no configuration to restore the old behavior.

## The fix — switch to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods are `async` and use `await`
- LINQ terminals → `ToListAsync`, `FirstAsync`, `CountAsync`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

> **Tip:** `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory. The actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
